fields.Image Description: The order of service and list of classmates and teachers the service was in honor of.  Emma Dory Powers, lived in Lakeland and attended Maryland State Teacher's College at Bowie; Tillman, worked with the federal government; Marvin Henry; Charles A. Thomas, had a large family in Muirkirk, went into the military, was a good hunter, and played sports; Malachi Hunter, was the best dancer among males in the class, was a "rascal" and altar boy. Teachers listed: Edgar A. Smith, Lakeland High School Principal "he wanted the best for you", taught algebra; Mrs. Myrtle M. Fentress "was a real leader who wanted the best for us," "if we ever needed anything, she was there", taught history and led the Glee Club, was found in her apartment after suffering blood pressure problems; Mrs. Vivian M. Ford, taught English to ninth graders only; Mrs. Marie Owens Halls was "mean" and soft-spoken, she wrote her day's objective on the board, "she was an excellent teacher" and a Prince Georgian. She went to Douglass and went to Howard, she was eventually afforded an opportunity to go to NYU for her Masters since Blacks weren't allowed to attend UMD.

fields.Image Description: Photo of Lakelander Myron Gray at Longfellow House Office Building greeting Congressman Nick Begich of Alaska, circa 1970-1971. Begich was also Myron's political science instructor at University of Alaska, which Myron attended in 1965 while in the Airforce; he enlisted for 49 months. Myron served as an "unofficial aide" of Congressman Begich saving newspaper articles of his features. Congressman Begich died in an airplane crash and was never recovered. His wife later took over his position. Woman pictured is congressional aide.

fields.Image Description:
Senior superlatives on the left side, opposite a history of the Lakeland school.

In August 1926, the Board of Education entertained the first request, by a Lakeland delegation, for the construction of a high school for Blacks in Lakeland, Maryland. The Board agreed with the understanding that the delegation should select the site. This was to be a community effort, i.e., the high school was to serve the communities of Bladensburg,
Brentwood, North Brentwood, Lakeland, Ammendale, Murkirk and Laurel. Lakeland had been chosen as the location, because of its central location. The Board of Education was to advance the funds for the purchase of the land and members of the communities were to repay the advance gradually, over a period of years. Money from the Rosenwald fund would pay for the construction of the building. Accordingly, early in 1928, the Board advanced the money for several lots in Block 14 (just west of the B&O railroad tracks) and a committee of representatives of the communities-chaired by J. W.C. Mack of Lakeland--was appointed to oversee the project until the building was completed and occupied.

The Lakeland High School opened in the fall of 1928, with two teachers and 45 students in grades 8 and 9. In July of 1929, W. J. Conway, chairman of the Lakeland High School P.T.A., presented to the Board of Education the balance of the obligation of $1600, which the communities had agreed to raise. On the 29 of July 1929, the Board instructed that "the
community be assured of the Board's Appreciation of this evidence of splendid cooperation."

Lakeland was one of the first high schools established for Blacks in Prince George's County and. is therefore very significant in the history of Black education. Over the years, the building served also as a junior high (after larger high schools had been opened), as a local elementary school, as a Special Education Center and most recently (in 1983) has been converted into a Korean Catholic Mission.

Second page is more cards - one reading "Drop In!", another reading "Good-bye! Please keep in touch!" and the final reading "It's a girl!" Handwritten on this final card is "John & Linda Mahoney." Written on the page below all these cards is a note from Pearl Lee Edwards, the donor ith some biographical details. She'd graduated in May 1972 from Bowie State with a degree in Elementary Education, and was "saying goodbye to the University of Maryland High Energy Physics Data Analyst Department," where she worked from August 1965 to January 1966. She was to move onto teaching.
Opposite is a 1969 letter addressed to all parents of children attending Lakeland Elementary, about the future of the school.  A note by Pearl, off to the side, gives context - Her daughter, four-year-old Monica, was in Miss Hecker's 'Head Start' class at the time. Written opposite of the letter is "IN THE BULLSEYE."

fields.Image Description: Announcement for Memorial Service on May 25, 2000 at First Baptist Church of Fairmont Heights. Reverend Mines led the service. The class convened every 5-10 years to celebrate classmates and teachers from Lakeland High School who passed away. The class set aside a month to honor them at a local churches in Fairmont Heights and Glenarden. The names of those passed were read and then a bel was rung. Rev. Rodney L. Young would often recruit the guest speakers. Family members of those passed were also in attendance.

fields.Image Description: Photo of Airforce Unit Class on Aircraft Jet maintenence on an F-101 airplane in Amarillo, Texas, circa 1964. Gray served as an airforce mechanic for jets. This moment represented a graduation to the next level; afterward, members were sent to different bases around the country. Gray was assigned to a military base in Myrtle Beach in South Carolina between 1964-1965. Although the training group contains mixed-races, several members were from the northeast (mainly New Jersey) and "got along pretty well because for the most part others had attended a mixed-race school."
